543
01:00:18,096 --> 01:00:22,590
The whole film crew's in there.
He still almost chickens out.

544
01:00:22,767 --> 01:00:26,965
I think he thought it was gonna
come back and finish him off.

545
01:00:27,138 --> 01:00:30,107
-What would you have done if it had?
-Ducked.

546
01:00:30,275 --> 01:00:31,970
Come on.

547
01:00:33,511 --> 01:00:36,139
Okay, here we go.

548
01:00:36,314 --> 01:00:40,045
Perfect. Just, just right there.
Thanks.

549
01:00:48,093 --> 01:00:50,084
-Well, cheers.
-Cheers.

550
01:00:50,261 --> 01:00:52,286
Cheers, Astrid.

551
01:00:53,431 --> 01:00:56,594
So we've got some catching up to do.

552
01:00:56,768 --> 01:00:59,328
Claire tells me you're quite an artist.

553
01:00:59,904 --> 01:01:02,498
-Not really...
-She's wonderful.

554
01:01:02,674 --> 01:01:07,168
In fact, Tricia Day accepted Astrid
for one of her watercolor classes.

555
01:01:07,345 --> 01:01:10,143
-At the museum?
-She loves Astrid's work.

556
01:01:10,315 --> 01:01:13,011
You should show him.

557
01:01:19,591 --> 01:01:21,957
They're really, really beautiful.

558
01:01:22,127 --> 01:01:24,994
She's never even studied.
She's self-taught.

559
01:01:25,163 --> 01:01:27,063
Is that right?

560
01:01:34,439 --> 01:01:35,599
Is she all right?

561
01:01:41,946 --> 01:01:44,676
-I know you're perfect.
-I'm not perfect.

562
01:01:44,849 --> 01:01:47,215
Of course you are.
You're my daughter.

563
01:01:47,385 --> 01:01:48,943
Hey.

564
01:01:49,954 --> 01:01:53,720
-Are you okay?
-Yeah. Just thinking.

565
01:01:58,263 --> 01:02:01,926
-Are you getting my letters?
-Yes.

566
01:02:02,100 --> 01:02:05,228
-I can never be sure.
-I get them.

567
01:02:09,040 --> 01:02:12,066
Why doesn't she have any children?

568
01:02:12,243 --> 01:02:14,711
She can't have them.

569
01:02:15,747 --> 01:02:17,305
You dress like her now.

570
01:02:21,085 --> 01:02:23,553
She takes me shopping.

571
01:02:26,224 --> 01:02:28,624
What's her husband like?

572
01:02:30,595 --> 01:02:32,529
He's nice.

573
01:02:32,697 --> 01:02:35,165
He's gone a lot.

574
01:02:36,801 --> 01:02:40,168
So you spend most
of your time with Claire?

575
01:02:41,773 --> 01:02:43,263
Yeah.

576
01:02:44,542 --> 01:02:46,100
I'd like to meet her.

577
01:02:47,045 --> 01:02:48,342
Why?

578
01:02:49,514 --> 01:02:52,108
Because you don't want me to.

579
01:02:57,689 --> 01:03:00,283
Who did this belong to?

580
01:03:00,792 --> 01:03:05,161
That was my great aunt's
on my father's side.

581
01:03:05,330 --> 01:03:09,460
She was a field nurse at Ypres.
Very, very brave woman.

582
01:03:09,968 --> 01:03:12,436
It's pretty, isn't it?

583
01:03:15,940 --> 01:03:19,205
-And whose was this?
-It was my mother's.

584
01:03:19,377 --> 01:03:24,872
My father gave it to her.
My parents were completely inseparable.

585
01:03:25,316 --> 01:03:27,546
Not at all like Mark and I.

586
01:03:30,121 --> 01:03:33,579
I hate it when he has
to go away for so long.

587
01:03:35,493 --> 01:03:39,429
-Why don't you go with him?
-He says it slows him down.

588
01:03:44,536 --> 01:03:49,439
-I think it's because he's having an affair.
-He wouldn't have an affair.

589
01:03:49,607 --> 01:03:51,905
He loves you.

590
01:03:52,110 --> 01:03:57,275
Yeah, I know. If he did,
I would never know about it.

591
01:03:57,448 --> 01:03:59,439
You're just being paranoid.

592
01:03:59,617 --> 01:04:05,317
Yeah, that's what he says.
That can be very negative.

593
01:04:18,770 --> 01:04:21,864
-Should I put this here?
-Yeah, perfect.

594
01:04:22,040 --> 01:04:24,406
Everything ready inside?

595
01:04:30,949 --> 01:04:34,783
-You're leaving tomorrow?
-In the morning.

596
01:04:36,120 --> 01:04:39,419
I bet Claire would
love to go with you.

597
01:04:40,058 --> 01:04:44,085
Coordinating our schedules is difficult.

598
01:04:44,262 --> 01:04:47,720
She's not working.
I mean, she could fit into yours.

599
01:04:47,899 --> 01:04:52,336
What about you?
Doesn't she need to be here for you?

600
01:04:53,137 --> 01:04:54,399
Yeah.

601
01:04:56,207 --> 01:05:01,304
How is she these days, when I'm gone?
She okay?

602
01:05:01,479 --> 01:05:03,071
She's fine.

603
01:05:03,247 --> 01:05:05,738
-Why do you ask?
-No reason.

604
01:05:27,372 --> 01:05:29,840
You're back early.

605
01:05:31,943 --> 01:05:35,003
How long has my mother
been writing you?

606
01:05:35,179 --> 01:05:40,242
Not long. We've only written
to each other a couple of times.

607
01:05:40,418 --> 01:05:43,683
-Why didn't you tell me?
-She asked me not to.

608
01:05:45,056 --> 01:05:48,651
Well, she thought
that you wouldn't like it.

609
01:05:51,829 --> 01:05:56,357
Her letter was so powerful.

610
01:05:56,534 --> 01:05:58,502
She's so strong.

611
01:05:58,670 --> 01:06:02,902
And God, she's talented.

612
01:06:05,843 --> 01:06:07,435
We'd like to meet.

613
01:06:10,381 --> 01:06:12,542
Whose idea was that?

614
01:06:12,950 --> 01:06:14,212
Mine.

615
01:06:15,953 --> 01:06:18,148
I bet.

616
01:06:20,391 --> 01:06:23,918
-You know, I really love your work.
-What have you seen?

617
01:06:24,262 --> 01:06:26,594
Astrid showed me the collages...

618
01:06:26,764 --> 01:06:29,995
...and some of your earlier work
in the catalogues.

619
01:06:30,168 --> 01:06:33,262
Oh, I love the Polaroid installation.

620
01:06:33,438 --> 01:06:35,303
Really? Why?

621
01:06:37,942 --> 01:06:39,273
I don't know.

622
01:06:40,211 --> 01:06:42,111
Well, because...

623
01:06:42,280 --> 01:06:44,578
Well, because it's great.

624
01:06:46,451 --> 01:06:52,287
-I'm actually very visual myself.
-A kindred spirit.

625
01:06:53,958 --> 01:06:57,257
It must be difficult
for you to work here.

626
01:06:58,429 --> 01:07:02,490
It is. I spend so much time
fighting off sexual advances...

627
01:07:02,667 --> 01:07:04,794
...I hardly have time to think.

628
01:07:07,638 --> 01:07:09,265
That was a joke.

629
01:07:13,077 --> 01:07:17,741
-Jailbird humor is hard to get sometimes.
-Sorry.

630
01:07:18,483 --> 01:07:21,145
So, you're an actress.

631
01:07:21,519 --> 01:07:26,354
-So glamorous.
-No, my career is a disaster.

632
01:07:26,924 --> 01:07:31,327
I think it's the process.
It, you know, may be too painful for me.

633
01:07:31,496 --> 01:07:34,090
You're such a sensitive person, it's...

634
01:07:34,265 --> 01:07:38,099
All that rejection has gotta be hard
on your self-esteem.

635
01:07:38,269 --> 01:07:43,400
I'm a typical Pisces, but that's
why Astrid and I get on so well.

636
01:07:43,708 --> 01:07:47,200
Scorpio and Pisces
understand each other.

637
01:07:47,378 --> 01:07:49,312
You're into astrology?

638
01:07:49,480 --> 01:07:54,281
She's not into astrology
just because she knows our signs.

639
01:07:55,753 --> 01:07:59,519
Astrid and I
used to understand each other.

640
01:07:59,857 --> 01:08:02,621
But she's become so secretive.

641
01:08:02,794 --> 01:08:08,494
Astrid isn't secretive at all.
We talk about everything, all the time.

642
01:08:10,067 --> 01:08:12,433
We just love her.

643
01:08:12,603 --> 01:08:14,969
She's doing so well.

644
01:08:15,139 --> 01:08:17,004
She's on the honor roll...

645
01:08:17,175 --> 01:08:21,839
...and we're just working to keep
that old grade point average up.

646
01:08:22,013 --> 01:08:25,210
Put a pyramid over her desk.
It improves memory.

647
01:08:25,383 --> 01:08:29,615
-My memory's fine.
-A pyramid? I hadn't thought of that.

648
01:08:29,787 --> 01:08:32,585
I do practice feng shui, though.

649
01:08:33,024 --> 01:08:35,686
