Just don't leave me.

701
01:12:20,184 --> 01:12:23,745
Unlike you, Claire, I work.
Remember?

702
01:12:24,188 --> 01:12:27,851
And she going with you,
your girlfriend?

703
01:12:28,759 --> 01:12:31,284
I've had it with this, Claire.

704
01:12:32,096 --> 01:12:34,189
I've really had it.

705
01:12:38,702 --> 01:12:40,636
Astrid?

706
01:13:00,357 --> 01:13:01,483
Astrid.

707
01:13:06,831 --> 01:13:09,493
Astrid, please.

708
01:13:44,902 --> 01:13:46,597
Claire?

709
01:13:48,739 --> 01:13:51,037
Are you awake?

710
01:14:04,855 --> 01:14:06,447
I'm sorry.

711
01:14:08,058 --> 01:14:09,525
Are you all right?

712
01:14:11,595 --> 01:14:13,153
Yeah.

713
01:14:14,965 --> 01:14:20,062
Take my advice.
Stay away from broken people.

714
01:14:22,206 --> 01:14:23,867
You can't send me back.

715
01:14:25,176 --> 01:14:27,371
He's not coming back, Astrid.

716
01:14:29,680 --> 01:14:32,547
He's gonna divorce me.

717
01:14:32,716 --> 01:14:37,085
You know, Claire,
it wouldn't be the worst thing.

718
01:14:44,261 --> 01:14:46,855
I'm cold.

719
01:14:48,499 --> 01:14:50,763
Real cold.

720
01:14:52,503 --> 01:14:54,903
Here. Get in here with me.

721
01:14:55,072 --> 01:14:57,370
Come on.

722
01:15:04,715 --> 01:15:06,046
Okay.

723
01:15:07,351 --> 01:15:10,286
Stay with me, okay?

724
01:15:14,458 --> 01:15:17,723
Stay with me, please.

725
01:15:31,642 --> 01:15:33,109
Claire.

726
01:15:36,847 --> 01:15:38,542
Claire.

727
01:15:59,603 --> 01:16:01,901
Claire, wake up! Claire!

728
01:16:04,808 --> 01:16:06,400
God!

729
01:16:13,884 --> 01:16:16,512
Claire, please.

730
01:16:19,523 --> 01:16:21,855
No!

731
01:16:43,447 --> 01:16:45,039
Astrid.

732
01:17:10,441 --> 01:17:12,102
What is it?

733
01:17:12,309 --> 01:17:13,799
I'm back in Mac.

734
01:17:13,977 --> 01:17:16,537
-Didn't they tell you?
-No.

735
01:17:17,081 --> 01:17:18,981
Claire's dead.

736
01:17:19,149 --> 01:17:21,743
She killed herself.

737
01:17:22,186 --> 01:17:24,814
-I'm sorry.
-No, you're not.

738
01:17:26,690 --> 01:17:31,821
-You poisoned her too, but with words.
-I told her what she already knew.

739
01:17:32,162 --> 01:17:34,221
You were just jealous.

740
01:17:34,398 --> 01:17:38,926
Of course I was jealous.
I live in a cell with a woman...

741
01:17:39,103 --> 01:17:43,472
...who has a vocabulary of 25 words.

742
01:17:44,041 --> 01:17:46,066
Why do you think they got you?

743
01:17:46,477 --> 01:17:50,072
To create a perfect family?
People get babies for that.

744
01:17:50,247 --> 01:17:52,738
Not teenagers recovering
from bullet wounds.

745
01:17:52,916 --> 01:17:56,647
You were on suicide watch. Don't think
it's the first time she tried it.

746
01:17:57,054 --> 01:18:00,023
It's just the first time
she pulled it off.

747
01:18:01,392 --> 01:18:04,293
I'm not coming back.

748
01:18:04,461 --> 01:18:07,123
I wanted to tell you that in person.

749
01:18:07,297 --> 01:18:09,527
I'm gonna leave you here, alone.

750
01:18:13,804 --> 01:18:15,863
I know you think I'm cruel.

751
01:18:16,039 --> 01:18:18,769
I'm trying to protect you
from those people.

752
01:18:18,942 --> 01:18:23,436
Those people are not the enemy,
Mother. We are. You and me.

753
01:18:24,081 --> 01:18:27,107
They don't hurt us.
We hurt them.

754
01:18:44,201 --> 01:18:46,795
You still ignoring me?

755
01:18:52,242 --> 01:18:55,973
I turn 18 Saturday.
I'm going to New York.

756
01:18:56,346 --> 01:18:58,780
I want you to come with me.

757
01:18:58,949 --> 01:19:00,814
I can't.

758
01:19:00,984 --> 01:19:05,045
Sure you can. Just leave.

759
01:19:18,302 --> 01:19:20,702
Is it your mother?

760
01:19:28,946 --> 01:19:30,607
Come on.

761
01:19:30,781 --> 01:19:35,184
I'll get a job. We'll find a place to live.
We'll be like we always talked about.

762
01:19:35,352 --> 01:19:40,790
I don't wanna go to New York.
I don't wanna be with you.

763
01:20:13,557 --> 01:20:17,493
She was with us for three years.
Her parents took her back.

764
01:20:17,995 --> 01:20:20,520
We think you'd really like it with us.

765
01:20:20,697 --> 01:20:24,133
There are lots of kids your age
in our neighborhood.

766
01:20:28,805 --> 01:20:30,602
Excuse me.

767
01:20:34,678 --> 01:20:39,843
Look. Don't worry about it.
She's had a very hard time recently.

768
01:20:40,017 --> 01:20:43,612
Let me just go talk to her, okay?
You're doing fine.

769
01:20:48,759 --> 01:20:50,989
So, what's wrong this time?

770
01:20:51,161 --> 01:20:53,755
I'm too old for them.

771
01:20:58,368 --> 01:21:00,666
Look, the Greenways are great.

772
01:21:01,605 --> 01:21:05,837
They've got a nice house
with an extra bedroom for you.

773
01:21:06,310 --> 01:21:08,744
They go to church.

774
01:21:08,912 --> 01:21:10,470
Schools are good.

775
01:21:10,647 --> 01:21:15,141
They don't smoke.
He makes his own beer.

776
01:21:17,054 --> 01:21:18,385
I want her.

777
01:21:29,466 --> 01:21:32,902
Workers of the world, arise.

778
01:21:35,072 --> 01:21:41,500
You've got nothing to lose but Visa card,
Happy Meal, and Kotex with wings.

779
01:21:44,348 --> 01:21:46,248
Christ, Thursday.

780
01:21:54,825 --> 01:21:59,558
-Hey, lazy cows, you want smoke?
-I quit for the baby, Rena.

781
01:21:59,730 --> 01:22:03,029
Why? You don't keep it, thank God.

782
01:22:04,768 --> 01:22:07,566
Hey, you, cheerleader.
You want smoke?

783
01:22:07,738 --> 01:22:10,571
Russian cigarettes. No cancer.

784
01:22:31,261 --> 01:22:32,523
Clothes.

785
01:22:35,198 --> 01:22:39,726
-That really is a nice color.
-It's gorgeous.

786
01:22:42,406 --> 01:22:46,206
-What's it made of?
-I don't know.

787
01:22:46,376 --> 01:22:49,607
Why don't you just try it on
and see how you look?

788
01:22:50,013 --> 01:22:52,982
-It's really nice.
-Okay, thank you.

789
01:22:53,517 --> 01:22:57,476
Hey, that's my dress.
These are all mine.

790
01:22:57,654 --> 01:23:02,785
So? You get good price for them.
What do you need expensive clothes for?

791
01:23:02,959 --> 01:23:06,827
-Melrose Place call you to be a star?
-Someone gave them to me.

792
01:23:06,997 --> 01:23:10,455
Even better. All profit.
That's why I love this country.

793
01:23:10,901 --> 01:23:13,597
Because it loves money
like I love money.

794
01:23:13,770 --> 01:23:17,763
-Hey. You make a price, I take 25%%.
-No.

795
01:23:19,209 --> 01:23:22,667
What, you think you're gonna sell it
all by yourself?

796
01:23:22,846 --> 01:23:29,251
I pay for stall, storage, gas. They pay you,
you pay me. You still make profit.

797
01:23:30,020 --> 01:23:31,544
Hey.

798
01:23:32,189 --> 01:23:36,523
Dead person who give you thing
don't care. The past is gone.

799
01:23:36,693 --> 01:23:40,686
Sentimental is stupid.
It's smart to make money.

800
01:23:41,998 --> 01:23:45,490
There's no price. How about $20?

801
01:23:45,669 --> 01:23:48,866
It's a Marc Jacobs dress.
It's been worn once.

802
01:23:49,840 --> 01:23:52,502
-Fifty?
-A hundred.

803
01:23:56,613 --> 01:24:00,049
Thank you. Let's go.

804
01:24:02,753 --> 01:24:04,744
-How was last night?
-It was fun.

805
01:24:04,921 --> 01:24:06,411
-Yeah?
-What'd you do?

806
01:24:06,590 --> 01:24:09,923
-Watched TV.
-Who were you with last night?

807
01:24:10,093 --> 01:24:11,754
-You know who I saw?
-Who?

808
01:24:11,928 --> 01:24:13,896
I saw Danny.

809
01:24:14,064 --> 01:24:17,090
-Don't you think Astrid would like him?
-No.

810
01:24:17,267 --> 01:24:19,064
Astrid?

811
01:24:21,271 --> 01:24:24,672
-I'm Hannah. This is Julie.
-Hi.

812
01:24:24,841 --> 01:24:28,641
We went to your house.
The lady said you'd be here, so...

813
01:24:28,812 --> 01:24:30,837
We visit your mother.

814
01:24:31,014 --> 01:24:34,381
She's our project
in Women's Studies.

815
01:24:35,585 --> 01:24:38,577
-What does she want?
-She didn't send us.

816
01:24:38,755 --> 01:24:40,188
We came on our own.

817
01:24:40,357 --> 01:24:44,589
She asked us to mail you
the interview, her show at Bergamot.

818
01:24:45,128 --> 01:24:48,188
We thought we could deliver it
and see if maybe...

819
01:24:48,365 --> 01:24:51,391
-Is that it?
-Yeah.

820
01:24:54,437 --> 01:24:56,302
Excuse me.

821
01:24:58,708 --> 01:25:02,872
-What do you talk about?
-All kinds of things. Art, music...

822
01:25:03,513 --> 01:25:05,481
She talks about you.

823
01:25:05,649 --> 01:25:07,048
Really?

824
01:25:08,852 --> 01:25:10,581
What does she say?

825
01:25:11,288 --> 01:25:13,381
Well, that you're in a...

826
01:25:13,557 --> 01:25:16,526
You know, fostered.

827
01:25:17,861 --> 01:25:21,353
Look, she feels really terrible
about what's happened.

828
01:25:21,531 --> 01:25:24,932
So you thought you'd come out
and what? Adopt me?

829
01:25:27,838 --> 01:25:30,932
You don't think she killed him,
do you?

830
01:25:32,142 --> 01:25:34,372
Something you should know.

831
01:25:34,544 --> 01:25:37,274
She did. I was there.

832
01:25:40,483 --> 01:25:43,975
Oleander's poisonous.
I don't know why people grow it.

833
01:25:44,354 --> 01:25:47,585
-Open the door!
-How dare you? You have no right!

834
01:25:47,757 --> 01:25:51,784
They can't keep me.
Don't worry, I'll be back in an hour!

835
01:26:38,275 --> 01:26:40,334
Who is that?

836
01:26:41,945 --> 01:26:43,606
I don't know.

837
01:26:43,780 --> 01:26:47,409
-You draw her all the time.
-I think her name was Annie.

838
01:26:47,584 --> 01:26:51,918
She's someone I remember.
I don't know who she was.

839
01:26:55,392 --> 01:26:57,917
Check it out, you guys.

840
01:26:58,094 --> 01:27:00,619
Rodeo Drive refugee.

841
01:27:00,897 --> 01:27:03,263
Excuse me, are you Rena Gruschenko?

842
01:27:03,433 --> 01:27:06,891
Gruschenka. If you come from INS,
I have a green card.

843
01:27:07,070 --> 01:27:10,597
I have been all over this junkyard
looking for you.

844
01:27:12,909 --> 01:27:17,369
You must be Astrid. I'm Susan Valeris,
your mother's lawyer.

845
01:27:21,051 --> 01:27:22,575
Cigarette?

846
01:27:25,822 --> 01:27:28,382
-Don't know why I never quit.
-I do.

847
01:27:28,692 --> 01:27:32,025
All the prisoners smoke.
You can offer them one.

848
01:27:32,195 --> 01:27:35,221
Your mother's proud of you
for not quitting school.

849
01:27:35,398 --> 01:27:39,835
You graduate soon. Are you making
any plans for your future?

850
01:27:40,003 --> 01:27:43,700
Yeah. I thought I'd be
a criminal lawyer.

851
01:27:44,174 --> 01:27:45,198
Really?

852
01:27:45,375 --> 01:27:49,539
Either that or a hooker
or garbage collector.

853
01:27:50,413 --> 01:27:52,938
Your mother said you'd be difficult.

854
01:27:53,116 --> 01:27:57,678
-Mother knows best.
-You've been through a terrible ordeal.

855
01:27:57,854 --> 01:28:02,621
Three foster homes, the shooting,
the suicide of a foster mother.

856
01:28:02,792 --> 01:28:04,783
I understand you were close.

857
01:28:04,961 --> 01:28:08,658
Did you ask your client
about her involvement with that?

858
01:28:08,832 --> 01:28:12,893
You can't blame her for the death
of a woman she met once.

859
01:28:13,069 --> 01:28:15,503
But I do blame her, Susan.

860
01:28:15,672 --> 01:28:18,505
That's pretty cynical, Astrid.

861
01:28:18,942 --> 01:28:22,309
You want me to lie for her
in court, is that it?

862
01:28:23,313 --> 01:28:26,146
Why do you hate her, Astrid?

863
01:28:27,484 --> 01:28:30,009
Because you think
she committed murder?

864
01:28:30,186 --> 01:28:32,177
Or because you feel abandoned?

865
01:28:32,822 --> 01:28:35,290
Talk to her. People do change.

866
01:28:37,227 --> 01:28:42,392
You should hear the way she talks
about you. She worries about you.

867
01:28:43,133 --> 01:28:45,897
She asked me to find out
if there's anything you need.

868
01:28:46,069 --> 01:28:48,867
Money for college? Car?

869
01:28:49,539 --> 01:28:53,066
There's money behind her.
Just tell me what you want.

870
01:29:26,042 --> 01:29:28,340
You are stupid girl.

871
01:29:29,779 --> 01:29:33,715
You walk away from money
to punish mother.

872
01:29:34,184 --> 01:29:35,481
You want car?

873
01:29:37,020 --> 01:29:39,887
You want art college?
All costs money.

874
01:29:42,659 --> 01:29:46,993
You don't know anything about this,
Rena, so just stay out of it.

875
01:29:51,434 --> 01:29:55,871
-I have plan for you, anyway.
-Yeah? What's that?

876
01:29:56,039 --> 01:29:58,371
Niki leave soon.

877
01:29:59,175 --> 01:30:01,609
And Yvonne is stupid girl.

878
01:30:01,778 --> 01:30:03,905
Making third baby.

879
01:30:04,080 --> 01:30:08,414
Every time she look at the window
to see baby's face, baby gone.

880
01:30:08,585 --> 01:30:12,146
Then she cries
like it's a big surprise.

881
01:30:12,989 --> 01:30:16,516
But you, you're a special girl.

882
01:30:19,696 --> 01:30:22,927
You stay, I make you partner.

883
01:30:24,400 --> 01:30:26,630
Stay here?

884
01:30:27,570 --> 01:30:30,403
What, you got better place to go?

885
01:30:36,446 --> 01:30:38,209
Then go see mother.

886
01:30:38,381 --> 01:30:41,680
She need something from you,
you need something from her.

887
01:30:41,851 --> 01:30:43,580
Go get it.

888
01:30:48,992 --> 01:30:50,960
Here she comes.

889
01:30:59,636 --> 01:31:01,467
Astrid, my God!

890
01:31:01,638 --> 01:31:05,404
What's wrong, Mom?
You don't like my outfit?

891
01:31:07,010 --> 01:31:09,979
I'll leave you two alone for a while.

892
01:31:22,759 --> 01:31:28,095
So, what's the story?
We didn't go to Mexico to buy DMSO?

893
01:31:28,264 --> 01:31:30,425
Barry beat you? He raped me?

894
01:31:30,600 --> 01:31:34,502
How bad does he have to be
to get you out of jail?

895
01:31:34,671 --> 01:31:39,472
I can't believe what's happened to you.
When I get out, I'll make it up.

896
01:31:39,642 --> 01:31:42,406
Who said you're getting out?

897
01:31:42,579 --> 01:31:46,777
I said I'd talk to you.
I didn't say I'd do it.

898
01:31:47,483 --> 01:31:49,542
Then what do you want?

899
01:31:49,719 --> 01:31:53,655
I have a deal to make. A trade.

900
01:31:55,124 --> 01:31:59,254
You tell me the truth,
I'll lie for you in court.

901
01:32:01,598 --> 01:32:05,329
-The truth about what?
-Everything you kept from me.

902
01:32:05,501 --> 01:32:09,699
-And if I don't?
-Then you can rot in here.

903
01:32:10,540 --> 01:32:13,168
I hate this look, by the way.

904
01:32:13,343 --> 01:32:18,872
You're a Sunset Boulevard motel,
a $20 hooker in the back of a car.

905
01:32:23,119 --> 01:32:25,610
Why did you murder Barry?

906
01:32:27,523 --> 01:32:30,549
If I submit to this, you'll testify?

907
01:32:30,727 --> 01:32:32,524
Yes.

908
01:32:35,431 --> 01:32:38,559
Self-defense. He was killing me.

909
01:32:40,303 --> 01:32:43,864
Claire did nothing to you.
Why'd you go after her?

910
01:32:44,040 --> 01:32:48,306
Claire went after herself.
I just showed her how to do it.

911
01:32:51,014 --> 01:32:52,743
Who was my father?

912
01:32:54,851 --> 01:32:58,252
Why do you always ask that?
It's ancient history.

913
01:32:58,421 --> 01:33:01,254
It's my ancient history.
Who was he?

914
01:33:02,425 --> 01:33:04,893
His name was Klaus Anders.

915
01:33:05,061 --> 01:33:07,996
-What'd he do?
-He was an artist.

916
01:33:10,667 --> 01:33:12,532
How did you meet?

917
01:33:12,702 --> 01:33:16,661
At Venice Beach, at a party.
He had the drugs.

918
01:33:18,508 --> 01:33:20,669
Did you love him?

919
01:33:21,311 --> 01:33:24,576
It was a long time ago.
I'm not the same person.

920
01:33:24,747 --> 01:33:29,241
Liar. You're exactly the same.
Answer the question.

921
01:33:29,419 --> 01:33:32,911
You're such a child,
taking my propaganda for truth.

922
01:33:33,089 --> 01:33:35,956
So set me straight.
Did you love him?

923
01:33:38,995 --> 01:33:43,329
We had a very sexual relationship.
One overlooks many things.

924
01:33:43,499 --> 01:33:46,468
You worshipped him.
I read it in your journal.

925
01:33:46,636 --> 01:33:51,403
"Worship" isn't exactly the word
we're looking for here.

926
01:33:52,041 --> 01:33:54,100
Who is Annie?

927
01:33:55,545 --> 01:33:56,569
What?

928
01:33:56,746 --> 01:33:59,374
Who is Annie, Mother?

929
01:34:04,487 --> 01:34:08,548
She was a neighbor who took in kids,
did people's laundry.

930
01:34:08,858 --> 01:34:15,161
-What did she look like?
-Dark, curly hair, freckles.

931
01:34:16,566 --> 01:34:19,160
Did she take care of me?

932
01:34:25,641 --> 01:34:28,940
How can you possibly
have remembered this?

933
01:34:35,885 --> 01:34:38,615
It will only hurt you.

934
01:34:43,559 --> 01:34:46,790
Imagine my life for a moment.

935
01:34:46,963 --> 01:34:53,027
How unprepared I was to be
the mother of a small child.

936
01:34:53,469 --> 01:34:59,169
I was used to having time to think
and you just wanted, wanted, wanted.

937
01:35:00,610 --> 01:35:03,238
I felt like a hostage.

938
01:35:03,413 --> 01:35:06,644
Can you understand
how desperate I was?

939
01:35:20,496 --> 01:35:24,125
I dropped you off
at her house one afternoon...

940
01:35:24,300 --> 01:35:27,963
...to go to the beach
with some friends.

941
01:35:28,905 --> 01:35:31,874
And one thing led to another.

942
01:35:33,509 --> 01:35:36,273
They had a place in Ensenada.

943
01:35:37,213 --> 01:35:39,408
It was wonderful.

944
01:35:39,916 --> 01:35:41,611
You can't imagine.

945
01:35:41,784 --> 01:35:44,150
To take a nap in the afternoon...

946
01:35:44,320 --> 01:35:48,723
...to make love all day if I wanted
and not have to think:

947
01:35:48,891 --> 01:35:52,657
What's Astrid doing? Where's Astrid?
Mommy, Mommy...

948
01:35:52,829 --> 01:35:55,127
...clinging to me like a spider.

949
01:35:55,298 --> 01:36:00,031
At the end, I just wanted
to throw you against a wall.

950
01:36:05,575 --> 01:36:07,941
How long were you gone?

951
01:36:10,613 --> 01:36:12,843
About a year.

952
01:36:13,649 --> 01:36:16,277
Give or take a few months.

953
01:36:17,487 --> 01:36:21,082
-My God.
-You're not asking the right question.

954
01:36:21,257 --> 01:36:25,921
Don't ask me why I left.
Ask me why I came back.

955
01:36:26,095 --> 01:36:28,086
You should've been sterilized.

956
01:36:28,264 --> 01:36:31,256
I could've left you there
but I didn't.

957
01:36:31,434 --> 01:36:35,564
Don't you understand?
For once, I did the right thing.

958
01:36:36,806 --> 01:36:39,468
When I came back, you knew me.

959
01:36:39,642 --> 01:36:44,944
You were sitting by the door.
You looked up and you reached for me.

960
01:36:45,114 --> 01:36:48,345
It was as if you'd been waiting
for me all along.

961
01:36:48,518 --> 01:36:52,511
I was always waiting for you.
That's the constant in my life.

962
01:36:52,688 --> 01:36:55,156
Waiting for you.
Will you come back?

963
01:36:55,324 --> 01:37:00,489
Will you forget that you tied me up in
front of a store or left me on a bus?

964
01:37:00,663 --> 01:37:03,427
-Are you still waiting?
-No.

965
01:37:04,100 --> 01:37:08,833
I stopped when Claire showed me
what it felt like to be loved.

966
01:37:09,539 --> 01:37:12,770
What did you think?
That I would amuse you?

967
01:37:12,942 --> 01:37:15,342
That's what babies are like, Mother.

968
01:37:15,511 --> 01:37:18,503
Did you think we'd talk
about Joseph Brodsky?

969
01:37:18,681 --> 01:37:22,242
I thought Klaus and I would
live happily ever after.

970
01:37:22,418 --> 01:37:25,751
Adam and Eve in a
vine-covered shack. I was crazy.

971
01:37:25,922 --> 01:37:28,914
-You were in love with him.
-I was, all right?

972
01:37:29,091 --> 01:37:32,424
I was in love with him,
baby makes three and all that crap.

973
01:37:32,595 --> 01:37:34,927
Then why did you leave him?

974
01:37:35,097 --> 01:37:39,932
-Why did you leave him?
-I didn't leave him. He left me.

975
01:37:42,672 --> 01:37:45,232
You wanna know about your father?

976
01:37:45,408 --> 01:37:48,844
He left us when you were
six months old for another woman.

977
01:37:49,011 --> 01:37:53,812
I never saw him again until he came
looking for you when you were 8.

978
01:37:53,983 --> 01:37:56,247
-He came to see me?
-Yes, he did.

979
01:37:56,419 --> 01:38:01,880
But it was too late. Why should I let
him see you after what he did to me?

980
01:38:02,058 --> 01:38:06,654
It wasn't about you! It was about me
and I wanted to see him!

981
01:38:06,829 --> 01:38:12,062
My whole life I've wanted to see him.
That decision was mine, not yours!

982
01:38:12,234 --> 01:38:16,364
Everything's always been about you,
never about me.

983
01:38:17,773 --> 01:38:22,176
I knew you were gonna kill Barry,
but you didn't even care.

984
01:38:22,345 --> 01:38:26,145
You didn't give a damn
about what that would do to me.

985
01:38:27,149 --> 01:38:30,141
I'll say whatever Susan wants,
but I gotta go.

986
01:38:30,319 --> 01:38:35,154
You don't just walk away from me.
I made you. I'm in your blood.

987
01:38:35,324 --> 01:38:39,090
You don't go anywhere
until I let you go.

988
01:38:39,261 --> 01:38:41,661
Then let me go.

989
01:38:46,268 --> 01:38:51,262
You look at me
and you don't like what you see.

990
01:38:52,108 --> 01:38:57,273
But this is the price, Mother.
The price of belonging to you.

991
01:38:57,780 --> 01:39:00,772
If I could, I'd take it all back.

992
01:39:02,318 --> 01:39:04,252
I would.

993
01:39:06,222 --> 01:39:09,885
Then tell me you don't
want me to testify.

994
01:39:10,760 --> 01:39:14,252
Tell me you don't want me like this.

995
01:39:18,768 --> 01:39:22,204
Tell me you would sacrifice
the rest of your life...

996
01:39:22,371 --> 01:39:25,431
...to have me back the way I was.

997
01:39:37,253 --> 01:39:40,279
Listen, forget it. A deal's a deal.

998
01:39:42,391 --> 01:39:44,484
Let's just leave it at that.

999
01:40:06,315 --> 01:40:09,773
Excuse me.
It's probably a waste of time...

1000
01:40:09,952 --> 01:40:15,083
...but I'm looking for someone who used
to come here. His name's Paul Trout.

1001
01:40:15,257 --> 01:40:17,623
-You Astrid?
-Yeah.

1002
01:40:26,936 --> 01:40:29,200
He said you'd turn up.

1003
01:40:33,509 --> 01:40:35,477
Thanks.

1004
01:42:05,067 --> 01:42:08,036
-What's going on?
-I don't know.

1005
01:42:13,909 --> 01:42:18,278
-Excuse me. Is it a recess?
-No. Jury's out.

1006
01:42:33,395 --> 01:42:36,330
Don't you need me to testify?

1007
01:42:37,399 --> 01:42:40,334
Your mother told me
to leave you alone.

1008
01:43:30,853 --> 01:43:32,718
What happened?

1009
01:43:35,891 --> 01:43:38,359
She let me go.

1010
01:43:56,045 --> 01:43:58,878
Two years after Paul and I
moved to New York...

1011
01:43:59,048 --> 01:44:01,812
...I received a letter
from my mother.

1012
01:44:01,984 --> 01:44:08,355
In it was the Los Angeles Times
Magazine, my mother on the cover.

1013
01:44:08,524 --> 01:44:12,290
A Santa Monica gallery had mounted
a showing of her work.

1014
01:44:12,461 --> 01:44:14,622
The Times included seven pages...

1015
01:44:14,797 --> 01:44:18,631
...of her hauntingly
distant prison collages.

1016
01:44:19,969 --> 01:44:26,340
She stares out from the cover,
the bars of her cell behind her.

1017
01:44:26,842 --> 01:44:28,605
Beautiful.

1018
01:44:28,777 --> 01:44:30,870
Dangerous.

1019
01:44:31,113 --> 01:44:33,047
Proud.

1020
01:44:34,216 --> 01:44:39,711
The Times said she was close to winning
a retrial after a first failed appeal.

1021
01:44:39,888 --> 01:44:43,153
They called her show a triumph.

1022
01:44:46,628 --> 01:44:52,089
It's too much to imagine her tempering
her joy with a moment of grief...

1023
01:44:52,267 --> 01:44:55,862
...a moment for what
that triumph had cost.

1024
01:44:56,705 --> 01:45:01,074
These suitcases are
a map of that country...

1025
01:45:01,243 --> 01:45:05,111
...a terrible country
I will never revisit.

1026
01:45:09,351 --> 01:45:11,319
Even so...

1027
01:45:12,521 --> 01:45:15,684
...I find myself thinking of her...

1028
01:45:16,358 --> 01:45:19,794
...wanting to feel that wind.

1029
01:45:21,296 --> 01:45:23,856
It's a secret wanting...

1030
01:45:24,133 --> 01:45:27,034
...like a song I can't stop humming...

1031
01:45:27,202 --> 01:45:30,660
...or loving someone
you can never have.

1032
01:45:34,843 --> 01:45:38,609
No matter how much
she's damaged me...

1033
01:45:39,681 --> 01:45:42,741
...no matter how flawed she is...

1034
01:45:43,619 --> 01:45:46,952
...I know my mother loves me.

1035
01:49:22,437 --> 01:49:23,426
[ENGLISH]

